        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Referring domain examples in practice</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — SaaS company link gap analysis</h3>
        <p>A project management SaaS ranked on page 2 for "team collaboration software." An Ahrefs audit revealed the top-ranking competitor had 412 referring domains; the SaaS had 89. The gap was not in content quality — it was in domain diversity. A 6-month digital PR campaign targeting industry blogs and comparison sites closed the gap to 280 referring domains, lifting the page to position 4.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Local business referral concentration</h3>
        <p>A legal firm had 340 backlinks but only 18 referring domains — nearly all links came from a single legal directory repeated across its regional editions. When that directory's authority dropped after a Google update, the firm's rankings dropped with it. Diversifying to 60+ referring domains across news sites, bar association pages, and client industry blogs stabilised rankings within 90 days.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — chasing backlink count instead of domain count</div>
          <p>Many site owners celebrate when they see their backlink count double after a mention in a large publication that links from 20 internal pages. In reality, those 20 backlinks count as 1 referring domain and have less combined impact than 5 links from 5 different authoritative sites. Measure referring domains, not total backlinks.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Referring domains vs domain authority — which metric to track</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Track referring domains when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Benchmarking against page 1 competitors</li>
              <li>Setting link-building campaign goals</li>
              <li>Diagnosing why rankings plateaued</li>
              <li>Measuring outreach campaign success</li>
              <li>Identifying link concentration risk</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Track domain authority when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Assessing overall site health</li>
              <li>Qualifying sites for outreach targeting</li>
              <li>Reporting to executives on brand authority</li>
              <li>Evaluating a potential link partner's value</li>
              <li>Comparing against industry benchmarks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for growing referring domains</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Publish original research and data.</strong> Studies, surveys, and proprietary datasets earn organic mentions from journalists and bloggers who need to cite their sources. A single well-promoted data piece can generate 20-50 new referring domains.</li>
          <li><strong>Run targeted digital PR campaigns.</strong> Identify journalists covering your industry and pitch genuinely newsworthy angles — product milestones, industry surveys, expert commentary on trending topics.</li>
          <li><strong>Guest post on industry publications.</strong> A single guest post on a domain authority 70+ publication adds a high-quality referring domain and establishes editorial relationships for future mentions.</li>
          <li><strong>Reclaim unlinked brand mentions.</strong> Use Ahrefs Alerts or Google Alerts to find instances where your brand is mentioned without a link. Reach out and request the link — conversion rates are typically 20-40% since they already know who you are.</li>
          <li><strong>Build free tools and calculators.</strong> Tools attract consistent natural links over time. A free keyword difficulty calculator or ROI estimator can earn dozens of referring domains without any active outreach.</li>
          <li><strong>Pursue resource page links.</strong> Pages listing the "best resources" on a topic are link-builder-friendly. Find them with search operators like <code>"resources" + your topic</code> and suggest your most comprehensive content.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common referring domain mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Buying links in bulk from link farms.</strong> A sudden spike of hundreds of low-quality referring domains triggers Google's spam filters and can result in manual actions.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring link velocity.</strong> Natural referring domain growth is gradual. If your profile grows from 50 to 500 domains in a week, it looks manipulative regardless of quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Forgetting to track lost referring domains.</strong> Domains can remove links or go offline. Monitor referring domain count monthly and proactively replace lost links.</li>
          <li><strong>Not vetting domain quality before outreach.</strong> Check that target sites have real organic traffic, publish original content, and are not part of private blog networks (PBNs).</li>
          <li><strong>Over-concentrating in a single industry category.</strong> A diverse link profile spans editorial, educational, directory, and community links — not just one type.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
